{"nodes":[{"content":"Device Guard deployment guide (Windows 10)","pos":[11,53]},{"content":"Microsoft Device Guard is a feature set that consists of both hardware and software system integrity hardening features that revolutionize the Windows operating system’s security.","pos":[67,246]},{"content":"Device Guard deployment guide","pos":[429,458]},{"content":"Applies to","pos":[462,472]},{"content":"Windows 10","pos":[479,489]},{"content":"Microsoft Device Guard is a feature set that consists of both hardware and software system integrity hardening features that revolutionize the Windows operating system’s security.","pos":[491,670]},{"content":"Windows 10 employs Device Guard as well as code integrity and advanced hardware features such as CPU virtualization extensions, Trusted Platform Module, and second-level address translation to offer comprehensive modern security to its users.","pos":[671,913]},{"content":"This guide explores the individual features in Device Guard as well as how to plan for, configure, and deploy them.","pos":[914,1029]},{"content":"Introduction to Device Guard","pos":[1034,1062]},{"content":"Today’s security threat landscape is more aggressive than ever before.","pos":[1064,1134]},{"content":"Modern malicious attacks are focused on revenue generation, intellectual property theft, and targeted system degradation, which results in financial loss.","pos":[1135,1289]},{"content":"Many of these modern attackers are sponsored by nation states with unknown motives and large cyber terrorism budgets.","pos":[1290,1407]},{"content":"These threats can enter a company through something as simple as an email message and can permanently damage its reputation for securing its software assets, as well as having significant financial impact.","pos":[1408,1613]},{"content":"Windows 10 introduces several new security features that help mitigate a large percentage of today’s known threats.","pos":[1614,1729]},{"content":"It is estimated that more than 300,000 new malware variants are discovered daily.","pos":[1731,1812]},{"content":"Unfortunately, companies currently use an ancient method to discover this infectious software and prevent its use.","pos":[1813,1927]},{"content":"In fact, current PCs trust everything that runs until malware signatures determine whether a threat exists; then, the antimalware software attempts to clean the PC, often after the malicious software’s effect has already been noticed.","pos":[1928,2162]},{"content":"This signature-based system focuses on reacting to an infection and ensuring that the particular infection does not happen again.","pos":[2163,2292]},{"content":"In this model, the system that drives malware detection relies on the discovery of malicious software; only then can a signature be provided to the client to remediate it, which implies that a computer must be infected first.","pos":[2293,2518]},{"content":"The time between the detection of the malware and a client being issued a signature could mean the difference between losing data and staying safe.","pos":[2519,2666]},{"content":"In addition to antimalware solutions, there are some “whitelisting” technologies available, including AppLocker.","pos":[2668,2780]},{"content":"These technologies perform single instance, or blanket-allow or blanket-deny rules for running applications.","pos":[2781,2889]},{"content":"Although this is more preventative than signature-based detection, it requires significant ongoing maintenance.","pos":[2890,3001]},{"content":"In Windows 10, these applications are most effective when they are deployed alongside Microsoft Device Guard.","pos":[3002,3111]},{"content":"Device Guard breaks the current model of detection first-block later, and allows only trusted applications to run, period.","pos":[3113,3235]},{"content":"This methodology is consistent with the successful prevention strategy for mobile phone security.","pos":[3236,3333]},{"content":"With Device Guard, Microsoft has changed how the Windows operating system handles untrusted applications, which makes its defenses difficult for malware to penetrate.","pos":[3334,3500]},{"content":"This new prevention versus detection model provides Windows clients with the necessary security for modern threats and, when implemented, makes most of today’s threats completely obsolete from day one.","pos":[3501,3702]},{"content":"Device Guard's features revolutionize the Windows operating system’s security by taking advantage of new virtualization-based security (VBS) options and the trust-nothing mobile device operating system model, which makes its defenses much more difficult for malware to penetrate.","pos":[3704,3983]},{"content":"By using configurable code integrity policies, organizations are able to choose exactly which applications are allowed to run in their environment.","pos":[3984,4131]},{"content":"Configurable code integrity is not limited to Windows Store applications and can be used with existing unsigned or signed Win32 applications, without the requirement that the application be repackaged.","pos":[4132,4333]},{"content":"In addition, configurable code integrity can be deployed as an individual feature if organizations don’t possess the required hardware for Device Guard.","pos":[4334,4486]},{"content":"Along with code integrity, Windows 10 leverages advanced hardware features such as CPU virtualization extensions, input/output memory management units (IOMMUs), Trusted Platform Module (TPM), and second-level address translation (SLAT) to offer comprehensive modern security to its users.","pos":[4487,4775]},{"content":"Device Guard deployed with configurable code integrity and Credential Guard will be among the most impactful client-side security deployments an organization can implement today.","pos":[4776,4954]},{"content":"In this guide, you learn about the individual features found within Device Guard as well as how to plan for, configure, and deploy them.","pos":[4955,5091]},{"content":"Device Guard with configurable code integrity is intended for deployment alongside additional threat-mitigating Windows features such as Credential Guard and AppLocker.","pos":[5092,5260]},{"content":"Device Guard overview","pos":[5265,5286]},{"content":"Device Guard is a feature set that consists of both hardware and software system integrity hardening features.","pos":[5287,5397]},{"content":"These features revolutionize the Windows operating system’s security by taking advantage of new virtualization-based security options and the trust-nothing mobile device operating system model.","pos":[5398,5591]},{"content":"A key feature in this model is called <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>configurable code integrity<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, which allows your organization to choose exactly which software or trusted software publishers are allowed to run code on your client machines—exactly what has made mobile phone security so successful.","pos":[5592,5862]},{"content":"In addition, Device Guard offers organizations a way to sign existing line-of-business (LOB) applications so that they can trust their own code, without the requirement that the application be repackaged.","pos":[5863,6067]},{"content":"Also, this same method of signing provides organizations with a way to trust individual third-party applications.","pos":[6068,6181]},{"content":"Device Guard—with configurable code integrity, Credential Guard, and AppLocker—is the most complete security defense that any Microsoft product has ever been able to offer a Windows client.","pos":[6182,6371]},{"content":"Advanced hardware features such as CPU virtualization extensions, IOMMUs, and SLAT, drive these new client security offerings.","pos":[6373,6499]},{"content":"By integrating these hardware features further into the core operating system, Windows 10 leverages them in new ways.","pos":[6500,6617]},{"content":"For example, the same type 1 hypervisor technology that is used to run virtual machines in Microsoft Hyper-V is used to isolate core Windows services into a virtualization-based, protected container.","pos":[6618,6817]},{"content":"This is just one example of how Windows 10 integrates advanced hardware features deeper into the operating system to offer comprehensive modern security to its users.","pos":[6818,6984]},{"content":"These hardware features are now available in consumer and enterprise PC markets and are discussed in detail in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hardware considerations<ept id=\"p1\">](#hardware-considerations)</ept> section.","pos":[6985,7160]},{"content":"Along with these new features, some components of Device Guard are existing tools or technologies that have been included in this strategic security offering to provide customers with the most secure Windows operating system possible.","pos":[7162,7396]},{"content":"Device Guard is intended as a set of client security features to be used in conjunction with the other threat-resistance features available in the Windows operating system, some of which are mentioned in this guide.","pos":[7397,7612]},{"content":"In addition to an overview of each feature, this guide walks you through the configuration and deployment of them.","pos":[7613,7727]},{"content":"Configurable code integrity","pos":[7731,7758]},{"content":"The Windows operating system consists of two operating modes: user mode and kernel mode.","pos":[7762,7850]},{"content":"The base of the operating system runs within the kernel mode, which is where the Windows operating system directly interfaces with hardware resources.","pos":[7851,8001]},{"content":"User mode is primarily responsible for running applications and brokering information to and from the kernel mode for hardware resource requests.","pos":[8002,8147]},{"content":"For example, when an application that is running in user mode needs additional memory, the user mode process must request the resources from kernel mode, not directly from RAM.","pos":[8148,8324]},{"content":"Code integrity is the component of the Windows operating system that verifies that the code Windows is running is trusted and safe.","pos":[8326,8457]},{"content":"Like the operating system, Windows code integrity also contains two primary components: kernel mode code integrity (KMCI) and user mode code integrity (UMCI).","pos":[8458,8616]},{"content":"KMCI has been used in recent versions of the Windows operating system to protect the kernel mode from running unsigned drivers.","pos":[8617,8744]},{"content":"Although effective, drivers are not the only route that malware can take to penetrate the kernel mode space of the operating system.","pos":[8745,8877]},{"content":"In Windows 10, however, Microsoft has raised the standard for kernel mode code out of the box as well as provided enterprises with a way to set their own UMCI and KMCI standards.","pos":[8878,9056]},{"content":"Beginning with the Code Integrity service itself and continuing through the policies a Windows client uses to verify that an application should be allowed to run, Microsoft has made Windows 10 more secure than any previous Windows release.","pos":[9057,9296]},{"content":"Historically, UMCI has been available only in Windows RT and on Windows Phone devices, which has made it difficult for these devices to be infected with viruses and malware.","pos":[9297,9470]},{"content":"In Windows 10, these same successful UMCI standards are available.","pos":[9471,9537]},{"content":"Historically, most malware has been unsigned.","pos":[9539,9584]},{"content":"By simply deploying code integrity policies, organizations will immediately protect themselves against unsigned malware, which is estimated to be responsible for more than 95 percent of current attacks.","pos":[9585,9787]},{"content":"By using code integrity policies, an enterprise can select exactly which binaries are allowed to run in both user mode and kernel mode, from the signer to the hash level.","pos":[9788,9958]},{"content":"When completely enforced, it makes user mode in Windows function like a mobile phone, by allowing only specific applications or specific signatures to be trusted and run.","pos":[9959,10129]},{"content":"This feature alone fundamentally changes the security in an enterprise.","pos":[10130,10201]},{"content":"This additional security is not limited to Windows apps and does not require that an application be rewritten to be compatible with your existing, unsigned applications.","pos":[10202,10371]},{"content":"You can implement configurable code integrity without enabling Device Guard, but it is intended to run in conjunction with Device Guard when supported hardware is available.","pos":[10372,10545]},{"content":"For more information about how to configure, deploy, and manage code integrity policies, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">](#code-integrity-policies)</ept> section.","pos":[10546,10703]},{"content":"Hardware security features and virtualization-based security","pos":[10707,10767]},{"content":"The Device Guard core functionality and protection start at the hardware level.","pos":[10771,10850]},{"content":"Devices that have processors equipped with SLAT technologies and virtualization extensions, such as Intel Virtualization Technology (VT-x) and AMD-V, will be able to take advantage of virtualization-based security (VBS) features that enhance Windows security.","pos":[10851,11110]},{"content":"Device Guard leverages VBS to isolate core Windows services that are critical to the security and integrity of the operating system.","pos":[11111,11243]},{"content":"This isolation removes the vulnerability of these services from both the user and kernel modes and acts as an impenetrable barrier for most malware used today.","pos":[11244,11403]},{"content":"One of these isolated services, called the Windows Code Integrity service, drives the Device Guard kernel mode configurable code integrity feature.","pos":[11404,11551]},{"content":"This prevents code that has penetrated the kernel mode operations from compromising the code integrity service.","pos":[11552,11663]},{"content":"Another Windows 10 feature that employs VBS is Credential Guard.","pos":[11664,11728]},{"content":"Credential Guard provides additional protection to Active Directory domain users by storing domain credentials within the virtualization container that hosts the Windows security services, such as code integrity.","pos":[11729,11941]},{"content":"By isolating these domain credentials from the active user mode and kernel mode, they have a much lower risk of being stolen.","pos":[11942,12067]},{"content":"For more information about how Credential Guard complements Device Guard, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Device Guard with Credential Guard<ept id=\"p1\">](#device-guard-with-credential-guard)</ept> section.","pos":[12068,12232]},{"content":"For information about how to enable Credential Guard, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable Credential Guard<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-credential-guard)</ept> section.","pos":[12233,12355]},{"content":"Device Guard with AppLocker","pos":[12359,12386]},{"content":"Although AppLocker is not considered a new Device Guard feature, it complements Device Guard functionality when enforced code integrity cannot be fully implemented or its functionality does not cover every desired scenario.","pos":[12390,12613]},{"content":"There are many scenarios in which code integrity policies would be used alongside AppLocker rules.","pos":[12614,12712]},{"content":"As a best practice, you should enforce code integrity policies at the most restrictive level possible for your organization, and then you can use AppLocker to fine-tune the restrictions to an even lower level.","pos":[12713,12922]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  One example in which Device Guard functionality needs AppLocker supplementation is when your organization would like to limit universal applications.","pos":[12925,13085]},{"content":"Universal applications have already been validated by Microsoft to be trustworthy to run, but an organization may not want to allow specific universal applications to run in their environment.","pos":[13086,13278]},{"content":"You can accomplish this enforcement by using an AppLocker rule.","pos":[13279,13342]},{"content":"AppLocker and Device Guard should run side-by-side in your organization, which offers the best of both security features at the same time and provides the most comprehensive security to as many devices as possible.","pos":[13343,13557]},{"content":"In addition to these features, Microsoft recommends that you continue to maintain an enterprise antivirus solution for a well-rounded enterprise security portfolio.","pos":[13558,13722]},{"content":"Device Guard with Credential Guard","pos":[13726,13760]},{"content":"Although Credential Guard is not a feature within Device Guard, many organizations will likely deploy Credential Guard alongside Device Guard for additional protection against credential theft.","pos":[13764,13957]},{"content":"Similar to virtualization-based protection of kernel mode code integrity, Credential Guard leverages hypervisor technology to protect domain credentials.","pos":[13958,14111]},{"content":"This mitigation is targeted at resisting the use of pass-the-hash and pass-the-ticket techniques.","pos":[14112,14209]},{"content":"By employing multifactor authentication with Credential Guard, organizations can gain additional protection against such threats.","pos":[14210,14339]},{"content":"For information about how to deploy Credential Guard to your Windows 10 Enterprise clients, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable Credential Guard<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-cg)</ept> section.","pos":[14340,14486]},{"content":"In addition to the client-side enablement of Credential Guard, organizations can deploy mitigations at both the CA and domain controller level to help prevent credential theft.","pos":[14487,14663]},{"content":"Microsoft will be releasing details about these additional mitigations in the future.","pos":[14664,14749]},{"content":"Unified manageability","pos":[14753,14774]},{"content":"You can easily manage Device Guard features by using the familiar enterprise and client-management tools that IT pros use every day.","pos":[14778,14910]},{"content":"Use the following management tools to enable and manage Device Guard:","pos":[14911,14980]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Group Policy<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[14986,15003]},{"content":"Windows 10 provides an administrative template to configure and deploy the configurable code integrity policies for your organization.","pos":[15004,15138]},{"content":"This template also allows you to specify which hardware-based security features you would like to enable and deploy.","pos":[15139,15255]},{"content":"You can manage these settings along with your existing Group Policy Objects (GPOs), which makes it simple to implement Device Guard features.","pos":[15256,15397]},{"content":"In addition to these code integrity and hardware-based security features, you can use Group Policy to help you manage your catalog files.","pos":[15398,15535]},{"content":"For more information about catalog files, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Catalog files<ept id=\"p1\">](#catalog-files)</ept> section.","pos":[15536,15626]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Microsoft System Center Configuration Manager<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[15631,15681]},{"content":"You can use System Center Configuration Manager to simplify deployment and management of catalog files, code integrity policies, and hardware-based security features, as well as provide version control.","pos":[15682,15884]},{"content":"For more information about how to deploy catalog files by using System Center Configuration Manager, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Deploy catalog files with System Center Configuration Manager<ept id=\"p1\">](#deploy-cat-sccm)</ept> section.","pos":[15885,16084]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Microsoft Intune<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[16089,16110]},{"content":"In a future release of Microsoft Intune, organizations will be able to leverage Intune for deployment and management of code integrity policies and catalog files.","pos":[16111,16273]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Windows PowerShell<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[16278,16301]},{"content":"Windows PowerShell is primarily used to create and service code integrity policies.","pos":[16302,16385]},{"content":"These policies represent the most powerful component of Device Guard.","pos":[16386,16455]},{"content":"For a step-by-step walkthrough of how to create, audit, service, enforce, and deploy code integrity policies, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">](#code-integrity-policies)</ept> section.","pos":[16456,16634]},{"content":"These options provide the same experience you are used to in order to manage your existing enterprise management solutions.","pos":[16636,16759]},{"content":"For more information about how to manage and deploy Device Guard hardware and code integrity features in your organization, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Device Guard deployment<ept id=\"p1\">](#dg-deployment)</ept> section.","pos":[16760,16942]},{"content":"Plan for Device Guard","pos":[16947,16968]},{"content":"In this section, you will learn about the following topics:","pos":[16970,17029]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Approach enterprise code integrity deployment<ept id=\"p1\">](#approach-enterprise-code-integrity-deployment)</ept>.","pos":[17035,17131]},{"content":"Device Guard deployment in your organization requires a planned approach.","pos":[17132,17205]},{"content":"In this section, you get high-level recommendations for how to approach enterprise code integrity deployment in your organization.","pos":[17206,17336]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Device Guard deployment scenarios<ept id=\"p1\">](#device-guard-deployment-scenarios)</ept>.","pos":[17341,17413]},{"content":"When you plan for Device Guard deployment, Microsoft recommends that you categorize each device in your organization into a deployment scenario.","pos":[17414,17558]},{"content":"These scenarios will provide a roadmap for your Device Guard deployment.","pos":[17559,17631]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code signing adoption<ept id=\"p1\">](#code-signing-adoption)</ept>.","pos":[17636,17684]},{"content":"Code signing is important to the security that Device Guard provides.","pos":[17685,17754]},{"content":"This section outlines the options for code signing and the benefits and disadvantages of each method.","pos":[17755,17856]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hardware considerations<ept id=\"p1\">](#hardware-considerations)</ept>.","pos":[17861,17913]},{"content":"Several Device Guard features require advanced hardware.","pos":[17914,17970]},{"content":"This section outlines the requirements for each of those features and what to look for during your next hardware refresh.","pos":[17971,18092]},{"content":"Approach enterprise code integrity deployment","pos":[18097,18142]},{"content":"Enterprises that want to consider Device Guard should not expect deployment to their entire organization overnight.","pos":[18144,18259]},{"content":"Device Guard implementation requires that you plan for both end-user and IT pro impact.","pos":[18260,18347]},{"content":"In addition, the deployment of Device Guard features to your enterprise requires a planned, phased approach to ensure that end-user systems are fully capable and ready to enforce these new security restrictions.","pos":[18348,18559]},{"content":"Perform the following high-level tasks to approach the deployment of Device Guard to your enterprise:","pos":[18560,18661]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Group devices into similar functions<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[18667,18708]},{"content":"Categorize machines into the groups described in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Device Guard deployment scenarios<ept id=\"p1\">](#device-guard-deployment-scenarios)</ept> section.","pos":[18709,18842]},{"content":"This begins the roadmap for your Device Guard deployment and provides groups of easier and more difficult implementations.","pos":[18843,18965]},{"content":"From there, assess the quantity of necessary Device Guard policies.","pos":[18966,19033]},{"content":"The easiest solution is to lock down your entire enterprise, but it might not fit your individual departments’ needs.","pos":[19034,19151]},{"content":"To discover an appropriate number of policies for your organization, try to separate the defined groups into departments or roles.","pos":[19157,19287]},{"content":"Then ask some questions: What software does each department or role need to do their job?","pos":[19288,19377]},{"content":"Should they be able to install and run other departments’ software?","pos":[19378,19445]},{"content":"Do we need to create a base code integrity policy that aligns with our application catalog?","pos":[19446,19537]},{"content":"Should users be able to install any application or only choose from an “allowed” list?","pos":[19538,19624]},{"content":"Do we allow users to use their own peripheral devices?","pos":[19625,19679]},{"content":"These questions will help you discover the number of necessary policies for your organization.","pos":[19680,19774]},{"content":"Finally, try to focus on which people or departments would require an additional level of privileges.","pos":[19775,19876]},{"content":"For example, should department x be able to install and run application xyz, even though no other department does?","pos":[19877,19991]},{"content":"If the answer is yes and justifiable, you will need a secondary code integrity policy for that group.","pos":[19992,20093]},{"content":"If not, you will likely be able to merge several policies to simplify management.","pos":[20094,20175]},{"content":"For more information about configurable code integrity policies, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">](#code-integrity-policies)</ept> section.","pos":[20176,20309]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Create code integrity policies from “golden” PCs<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[20315,20368]},{"content":"After you create the groups of devices, you can create code integrity policies to align with those groups, similar to the way you would manage corporate images.","pos":[20369,20529]},{"content":"When you have separated these groups and set up golden PCs that mimic the software and hardware those individual groups require, create code integrity policies from each of them.","pos":[20530,20708]},{"content":"After you create these, you can merge these code integrity policies to create a master policy, or you can manage and deploy them individually.","pos":[20709,20851]},{"content":"For step-by-step instructions about how to create code integrity policies, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Create code integrity policies from golden PCs<ept id=\"p1\">](#create-code-integrity-policies-from-golden-pcs)</ept> section.","pos":[20852,21041]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Audit and merge code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[21047,21091]},{"content":"Microsoft recommends that you test code integrity policies in audit mode before you enforce them.","pos":[21092,21189]},{"content":"Audit mode allows administrators to run the code integrity policy on a system but not actually block anything.","pos":[21190,21300]},{"content":"Rather than not allowing applications to run, events are logged with each exception to the policy.","pos":[21301,21399]},{"content":"This way, you can easily highlight any issues that were not discovered during the initial scan.","pos":[21400,21495]},{"content":"You can create additional code integrity policies by using the audit events and merge them into the existing policy.","pos":[21496,21612]},{"content":"For more information about how to audit code integrity policies, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Audit code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">](#audit-code-integrity-policies)</ept> section.","pos":[21613,21758]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Assess LOB applications that are currently unsigned, and create a catalog file for them<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[21764,21856]},{"content":"Catalog files allow organizations to sign applications that do not currently possess digitally signed binaries or applications that a customer would want to add a secondary signature to.","pos":[21857,22043]},{"content":"These applications can be in-house applications or from third parties, and the process does not require any repackaging of the application.","pos":[22044,22183]},{"content":"When you create code integrity policies at a rule level above hash values, you will not discover unsigned applications.","pos":[22184,22303]},{"content":"To include these applications in your code integrity policies, simply create, sign, and deploy a catalog file.","pos":[22304,22414]},{"content":"For information about catalog files, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Catalog files<ept id=\"p1\">](#catalog-files)</ept> section.","pos":[22415,22500]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable desired hardware security features<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[22506,22552]},{"content":"Each type of device found in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Device Guard deployment scenarios<ept id=\"p1\">](#device-guard-deployment-scenarios)</ept> section takes advantage of different software and hardware integrity configurations.","pos":[22553,22742]},{"content":"You should assess hardware-based security features separately from code integrity policies because they provide complementary functionality.","pos":[22743,22883]},{"content":"For information about how to configure Device Guard hardware-based security features, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configure hardware-based security features<ept id=\"p1\">](#configure-hardware-based-security-features)</ept> section.","pos":[22884,23076]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Deploy code integrity policies and catalog files<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[23082,23135]},{"content":"After you have created and signed the necessary catalog files and created and audited code integrity policies, you are ready to deploy them in phases.","pos":[23136,23286]},{"content":"Microsoft strongly recommends that you deploy these components to a test group of users, even after your IT organization has tested and vetted them.","pos":[23287,23435]},{"content":"This provides a final quality control validation before you deploy the catalog files and policies more broadly.","pos":[23436,23547]},{"content":"For information about how to deploy catalog files with Group Policy, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Deploy catalog files with Group Policy<ept id=\"p1\">](#deploy-catalog-files-with-group-policy)</ept> section.","pos":[23548,23715]},{"content":"For additional information about how to deploy code integrity policies, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Deploy code integrity policies with Group Policy<ept id=\"p1\">](#deploy-code-integrity-policies-with-group-policy)</ept> section.","pos":[23716,23906]},{"content":"Device Guard deployment scenarios","pos":[23911,23944]},{"content":"To help simplify the deployment of Device Guard to your organization, Microsoft recommends that you group devices into the deployment scenarios described in this section.","pos":[23946,24116]},{"content":"Device Guard is not a feature that organizations will just simply “turn on”; rather, it typically requires a phased implementation approach.","pos":[24117,24257]},{"content":"To see where these scenarios fit into an overall Device Guard deployment approach, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Approach to enterprise code integrity deployment<ept id=\"p1\">](#approach-to-enterprise-code-integrity-deployment)</ept> section.","pos":[24258,24459]},{"content":"Fixed-workload devices","pos":[24463,24485]},{"content":"The lists of approved applications on fixed-workload devices rarely change as they perform the same tasks day after day.","pos":[24489,24609]},{"content":"Examples of such devices include kiosks, point-of-sale systems, and call center PCs.","pos":[24610,24694]},{"content":"These devices could easily employ the full capabilities of Device Guard and would require little management or policy modification.","pos":[24695,24826]},{"content":"Device Guard implementation to these devices is painless and requires little ongoing administration.","pos":[24827,24927]},{"content":"With Device Guard fully implemented, users are able to run only those applications that the IT department installs, manages, and trusts.","pos":[24928,25064]},{"content":"Device Guard components that are applicable to fixed-workload devices include:","pos":[25065,25143]},{"content":"KMCI VBS protection","pos":[25149,25168]},{"content":"Enforced UMCI policy","pos":[25173,25193]},{"content":"Fully managed devices","pos":[25197,25218]},{"content":"Fully managed devices are those for which the IT department restricts the software that is installed and run on them, but allows users to request installation of additional software or provides a list of approved software in an application catalog.","pos":[25222,25470]},{"content":"Examples of such devices include locked-down, company-owned desktops and laptops.","pos":[25471,25552]},{"content":"With these devices, establish an initial baseline code integrity policy and enforce the code integrity policy.","pos":[25553,25663]},{"content":"The IT department manages the policies and updates the devices when new applications are approved or are provided in the System Center Configuration Manager catalog.","pos":[25664,25829]},{"content":"Device Guard components that are applicable to fully managed devices include:","pos":[25830,25907]},{"content":"KMCI VBS protection","pos":[25913,25932]},{"content":"Enforced UMCI policy","pos":[25937,25957]},{"content":"In this scenario, an application list is provided and trusted, and the trust policy is constantly re-evaluated when a user requests a new application.","pos":[25959,26109]},{"content":"When an application is trusted across all of these devices, new user requests for that application do not require a policy update (alignment with application catalog).","pos":[26110,26277]},{"content":"In addition, you can couple this with an onboarding process for new applications that you should add to the central application catalog.","pos":[26278,26414]},{"content":"Initial implementation of Device Guard to fully managed devices is simple but does require more administrative overhead to manage trusted signatures of newly requested and approved applications.","pos":[26415,26609]},{"content":"Lightly managed devices","pos":[26613,26636]},{"content":"Lightly managed devices are company-owned machines over which users have full control, which includes what is installed on them.","pos":[26640,26768]},{"content":"These devices run the organization’s antivirus solution and client management tools but are not restricted by software request or compliance policies.","pos":[26769,26919]},{"content":"Device Guard components that are applicable to lightly managed devices include:","pos":[26921,27000]},{"content":"KMCI VBS protection","pos":[27006,27025]},{"content":"UMCI policy in Audit mode","pos":[27030,27055]},{"content":"Bring Your Own Device","pos":[27059,27080]},{"content":"Device Guard is not a good way to manage devices in a Bring Your Own Device (BYOD) model.","pos":[27084,27173]},{"content":"When employees are allowed to bring their own devices, the management of user-mode applications on them can make it difficult for users to use their own devices when they are not at work.","pos":[27174,27361]},{"content":"In addition, Device Guard functionality is difficult to maintain from an administrative perspective.","pos":[27362,27462]},{"content":"For devices in this group, explore alternate hardening and security features with MDM-based conditional access solutions, such as Microsoft Intune.","pos":[27463,27610]},{"content":"Code signing adoption","pos":[27615,27636]},{"content":"Code signing is crucial to the successful implementation of configurable code integrity policies.","pos":[27638,27735]},{"content":"These policies can trust the signing certificates from both independent software vendors and customers.","pos":[27736,27839]},{"content":"In Windows 10, all Windows Store applications are signed.","pos":[27840,27897]},{"content":"Also, you can easily trust any other signed application by adding the signing certificate to the code integrity policy.","pos":[27898,28017]},{"content":"For unsigned applications, customers have multiple options for signing them so that code integrity policies can trust them.","pos":[28018,28141]},{"content":"The first option is traditional embedded code signing.","pos":[28142,28196]},{"content":"Organizations that have in-house development teams can incorporate binary code signing into their application development process, and then simply add the signing certificate to their code integrity policies.","pos":[28197,28405]},{"content":"The second option for signing unsigned applications is to use catalog files.","pos":[28406,28482]},{"content":"In Windows 10, customers have the ability to create catalog files as they monitor the installation and initial run of an application.","pos":[28483,28616]},{"content":"For more information about signing existing unsigned LOB applications or third-party applications, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Existing line-of-business applications<ept id=\"p1\">](#existing-line-of-business-applications)</ept> section.","pos":[28617,28814]},{"content":"Existing line-of-business applications","pos":[28820,28858]},{"content":"Until now, existing LOB applications were difficult to trust if they were signed by a source other than the Windows Store or not signed at all.","pos":[28860,29003]},{"content":"With Windows 10, signing your existing LOB and third-party unsigned applications is simplified.","pos":[29004,29099]},{"content":"This new signing method does not require that applications be repackaged in any way.","pos":[29100,29184]},{"content":"With catalog files, administrators can sign these unsigned applications simply by monitoring for an installation and initial startup.","pos":[29185,29318]},{"content":"By using this monitoring information, an administrator can generate a catalog file.","pos":[29319,29402]},{"content":"Catalog files are simply Secure Hash Algorithm 2 (SHA2) hash lists of discovered binaries.","pos":[29403,29493]},{"content":"These binaries’ hash values are updated every time an application is updated and therefore require an updated catalog file.","pos":[29494,29617]},{"content":"For simplified administration, consider incorporating embedded code signing into your application development process.","pos":[29618,29736]},{"content":"For more information about how to generate catalog files, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Catalog files<ept id=\"p1\">](#catalog-files)</ept> section.","pos":[29737,29843]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Catalog files are lists of individual binaries’ hash values.","pos":[29846,29917]},{"content":"If the scanned application is updated, you will need to create a new catalog file.","pos":[29918,30000]},{"content":"That said, binary signing is still highly recommended for any future applications so that no catalog files are needed.","pos":[30001,30119]},{"content":"When you create a catalog file, you must sign it by using enterprise public key infrastructure (PKI), or a purchased code signing certificate.","pos":[30122,30264]},{"content":"When signed, code integrity policies can trust the signer or signing certificate of those files.","pos":[30265,30361]},{"content":"For information about catalog file signing, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Catalog files<ept id=\"p1\">](#catalog-files)</ept> section.","pos":[30362,30454]},{"content":"Application development","pos":[30458,30481]},{"content":"Although in-house applications can be signed after packaging by using catalog files, Microsoft strongly recommends that embedded code signing be incorporated into your application development process.","pos":[30485,30685]},{"content":"When signing applications, simply add the code signing certificate used to sign your applications to your code integrity policy.","pos":[30686,30814]},{"content":"This ensures that your code integrity policy will trust any future application that is signed with that certificate.","pos":[30815,30931]},{"content":"Embedding code signing into any in-house application development process is beneficial to your IT organization as you implement code integrity policies.","pos":[30932,31084]},{"content":"Hardware considerations","pos":[31089,31112]},{"content":"Careful consideration about which hardware vendor and specific models to purchase during your next hardware refresh is vitally important to the success of your organization’s Device Guard implementation efforts.","pos":[31114,31325]},{"content":"In alignment with your current hardware life cycle, consider the process that is discussed in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Approach enterprise code integrity deployment<ept id=\"p1\">](#approach-enterprise-code-integrity-deployment)</ept> section when you determine the appropriate order of hardware replacement in your organization.","pos":[31326,31614]},{"content":"Device Guard should be deployed in phases; therefore, you have time to methodically plan for its implementation.","pos":[31615,31727]},{"content":"Different hardware features are required to implement the various features of Device Guard.","pos":[31729,31820]},{"content":"There will likely be some individual features that you will be able to enable with your current hardware and some that you will not.","pos":[31821,31953]},{"content":"However, for organizations that want to implement Device Guard in its entirety, several advanced hardware features will be required.","pos":[31954,32086]},{"content":"For additional details about the hardware features that are required for Device Guard components, see the following table.","pos":[32087,32209]},{"content":"Requirement","pos":[32327,32338]},{"content":"Description","pos":[32361,32372]},{"content":"Windows 10 Enterprise","pos":[32438,32459]},{"content":"The PC must be running Windows 10 Enterprise.","pos":[32489,32534]},{"content":"UEFI firmware version 2.3.1 or higher with UEFI Secure Boot and Platform Secure Boot","pos":[32588,32672]},{"content":"UEFI Secure Boot ensures that the device boots only authorized code.","pos":[32702,32770]},{"content":"Additionally, Boot Integrity, also known as Platform Secure Boot must be supported.","pos":[32771,32854]},{"content":"You can validate it against the following Windows Hardware Compatibility Program requirements:","pos":[32855,32949]},{"content":"System.Fundamentals.Firmware.UEFISecureBoot","pos":[32967,33010]},{"content":"System.Fundamentals.Firmware.CS.UEFISecureBoot.ConnectedStandby","pos":[33139,33202]},{"content":"Virtualization extensions","pos":[33397,33422]},{"content":"The following virtualization extensions are required to support virtualization-based security:","pos":[33452,33546]},{"content":"Intel VT-x or AMD-V","pos":[33560,33579]},{"content":"Second Level Address Translation","pos":[33589,33621]},{"content":"Firmware lock","pos":[33682,33695]},{"content":"The firmware setup should be locked to prevent other operating systems from starting and to prevent changes to the UEFI settings.","pos":[33734,33863]},{"content":"Work with your hardware manufacturer to ensure that the devices are Device Guard ready.","pos":[33880,33967]},{"content":"You should require a firmware password or higher authentication to change firmware settings.","pos":[33984,34076]},{"content":"x64 architecture","pos":[34140,34156]},{"content":"The features that virtualization-based security uses in the Windows hypervisor can only run on a 64-bit PC.","pos":[34186,34293]},{"content":"A VT-d or AMD-Vi IOMMU (Input/output memory management unit)","pos":[34347,34407]},{"content":"In Windows 10, an IOMMU enhances system resiliency against memory attacks.","pos":[34437,34511]},{"content":"Secure firmware update process","pos":[34564,34594]},{"content":"To verify that the firmware complies with the secure firmware update process, you can validate it against the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>System.Fundamentals.Firmware.UEFISecureBoot<ept id=\"p1\">](http://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/hardware/dn932805.aspx#system-fundamentals-firmware-uefisecureboot)</ept> Windows Hardware Compatibility Program requirement.","pos":[34624,34941]},{"content":"Device Guard relies on the security of the underlying hardware and firmware.","pos":[34948,35024]},{"content":"It is critical to keep the firmware updated with the latest security fixes.","pos":[35025,35100]},{"content":"Signed processor microcode updates","pos":[35154,35188]},{"content":"If the processor supports it, you must require signed microcode updates.","pos":[35218,35290]},{"content":"Device Guard deployment","pos":[35328,35351]},{"content":"In this section, you learn about the following topics:","pos":[35353,35407]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configure hardware-based security features<ept id=\"p1\">](#configure-hardware-based-security-features)</ept>.","pos":[35413,35503]},{"content":"This section explains how to enable the hardware-based security features in Device Guard.","pos":[35504,35593]},{"content":"Also, you verify that the features are enabled by using both Windows Management Infrastructure (WMI) and Msinfo32.exe.","pos":[35594,35712]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Catalog files<ept id=\"p1\">](#catalog-files)</ept>.","pos":[35717,35749]},{"content":"In this section, you create, sign, and deploy catalog files.","pos":[35750,35810]},{"content":"You deploy the catalog files by using both Group Policy and System Center Configuration Manager.","pos":[35811,35907]},{"content":"Also, you use System Center Configuration Manager to inventory the deployed catalog files for reporting purposes.","pos":[35908,36021]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">](#code-integrity-policies)</ept>.","pos":[36026,36078]},{"content":"This section provides information on how to create, audit, service, merge, deploy, and remove signed and unsigned configurable code integrity policies.","pos":[36079,36230]},{"content":"Configure hardware-based security features","pos":[36235,36277]},{"content":"Hardware-based security features make up a large part of Device Guard security offerings.","pos":[36279,36368]},{"content":"VBS reinforces the most important feature of Device Guard: configurable code integrity.","pos":[36369,36456]},{"content":"There are three steps to configure hardware-based security features in Device Guard:","pos":[36457,36541]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Verify that hardware requirements are met and enabled<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[36547,36605]},{"content":"Verify that your client machines possess the necessary hardware to run these features.","pos":[36606,36692]},{"content":"A list of hardware requirements for the hardware-based security features is available in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hardware considerations<ept id=\"p1\">](#hardware-considerations)</ept> section.","pos":[36693,36846]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable the necessary Windows features<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[36851,36893]},{"content":"There are several ways to enable the Windows features required for hardware-based security.","pos":[36894,36985]},{"content":"For details on which Windows features are needed, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows feature requirements for virtualization-based security<ept id=\"p1\">](#windows-feature-requirements-for-virtualization-based-security)</ept> section.","pos":[36986,37182]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enable desired features<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[37187,37215]},{"content":"When the necessary hardware and Windows features have been enabled, you are ready to enable the desired hardware-based security features.","pos":[37216,37353]},{"content":"For UEFI Secure Boot, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable UEFI Secure Boot<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-unified-extensible-interface-secure-boot)</ept> section.","pos":[37354,37468]},{"content":"For information about how to enable VBS protection of the KMCI service, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable virtualization-based protection of kernel mode code integrity<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-virtualbased)</ept> section.","pos":[37469,37650]},{"content":"Finally, for information about how to enable Credential Guard, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable Credential Guard<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-credential-guard)</ept> section.","pos":[37651,37782]},{"content":"Windows feature requirements for virtualization-based security","pos":[37788,37850]},{"pos":[37852,38105],"content":"In addition to the hardware requirements found in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hardware considerations<ept id=\"p1\">](#hardware-considerations)</ept> section, you must enable certain operating system features before you can enable VBS: Microsoft Hyper-V and isolated user mode (shown in Figure 1)."},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  You can configure these features manually by using Windows PowerShell or Deployment Image Servicing and Management.","pos":[38108,38234]},{"content":"For specific information about these methods, refer to the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Credential Guard documentation<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?LinkId=624529)</ept>.","pos":[38235,38376]},{"content":"figure 1","pos":[38381,38389]},{"content":"Figure 1.","pos":[38421,38430]},{"content":"Enable operating system features for VBS","pos":[38431,38471]},{"content":"After you enable these features, you can configure any hardware-based security features you want.","pos":[38473,38570]},{"content":"For information about how to enable virtualization-based protection of kernel-mode code integrity, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable virtualization-based protection of kernel-mode code integrity<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-virtualization-based-protection-of-kernel-mode-code-integrity)</ept> section.","pos":[38571,38828]},{"content":"For information about how to enable UEFI Secure Boot, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable UEFI Secure Boot<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-unified-extensible-interface-secure-boot)</ept> section.","pos":[38829,38975]},{"content":"Finally, for additional information about how to enable Credential Guard, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Enable Credential Guard<ept id=\"p1\">](#enable-credential-guard)</ept> section.","pos":[38976,39118]},{"content":"Enable Unified Extensible Firmware Interface Secure Boot","pos":[39124,39180]},{"content":"Before you begin this process, verify that the target device meets the hardware requirements for UEFI Secure Boot that are laid out in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hardware considerations<ept id=\"p1\">](#hardware-considerations)</ept> section.","pos":[39182,39381]},{"content":"There are two options to configure UEFI Secure Boot: manual configuration of the appropriate registry keys and Group Policy deployment.","pos":[39382,39517]},{"content":"Complete the following steps to manually configure UEFI Secure Boot on a computer running Windows 10:","pos":[39518,39619]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  There are two platform security levels for Secure Boot: stand-alone Secure Boot and Secure Boot with DMA protection.","pos":[39622,39749]},{"content":"DMA protection provides additional memory protection but will be enabled only on systems whose processors include DMA protection (IOMMU) technologies.","pos":[39750,39900]},{"content":"Without the presence of IOMMUs and with DMA protection disabled, customers will lose protection from driver-based attacks.","pos":[39901,40023]},{"pos":[40029,40135],"content":"Navigate to the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>HKEY<ph id=\"ph1\">\\_</ph>LOCAL<ph id=\"ph2\">\\_</ph>MACHINE<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>SYSTEM<ph id=\"ph4\">\\\\</ph>CurrentControlSet<ph id=\"ph5\">\\\\</ph>Control<ph id=\"ph6\">\\\\</ph>DeviceGuard<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> registry subkey."},{"pos":[40140,40207],"content":"Set the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>EnableVirtualizationBasedSecurity DWORD<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> value to <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>1<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>."},{"pos":[40212,40283],"content":"Set the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>RequirePlatformSecurityFeatures DWORD<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> value as appropriate:"},{"pos":[40293,40354],"content":"Set this value to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>1<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to enable the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Secure Boot<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> option."},{"pos":[40363,40444],"content":"Set this value to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>2<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> to enable the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Secure Boot with DMA Protection<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> option."},{"content":"Restart the client machine.","pos":[40450,40477]},{"content":"Unfortunately, it would be time consuming to perform these steps manually on every protected machine in your enterprise.","pos":[40479,40599]},{"content":"Group Policy offers a much simpler way to deploy UEFI Secure Boot to your organization.","pos":[40600,40687]},{"content":"This example creates a test organizational unit (OU) called <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>DG Enabled PCs<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>.","pos":[40688,40765]},{"content":"If you prefer to link the policy to an existing OU, and then scope the GPO by using appropriately named computer security groups, you can certainly do so.","pos":[40766,40920]},{"pos":[40923,41087],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Microsoft recommends that you test-enable this feature on a group of test machines before you deploy it to machines that are currently deployed to users."},{"content":"Use Group Policy to deploy Secure Boot","pos":[41091,41129]},{"pos":[41178,41318],"content":"To create a new GPO, right-click the OU to which you want to link the GPO, and then click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Create a GPO in this domain, and Link it here<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"figure 2","pos":[41326,41334]},{"content":"Figure 2.","pos":[41370,41379]},{"content":"Create a new OU-linked GPO","pos":[41380,41406]},{"content":"Name the new GPO <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Contoso Secure Boot GPO Test<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[41412,41462]},{"content":"This example uses <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Contoso Secure Boot GPO Test<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> as the name of the GPO.","pos":[41463,41535]},{"content":"You can choose any name for this example.","pos":[41536,41577]},{"content":"Ideally, the name would align with your existing GPO naming convention.","pos":[41578,41649]},{"pos":[41655,41748],"content":"To open the Group Policy Management Editor, right-click the new GPO, and then click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Edit<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"Within the selected GPO, navigate to Computer Configuration<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Administrative Templates<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>Device Guard.","pos":[41754,41862]},{"content":"Then, right-click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Turn On Virtualization Based Security<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and then click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Edit<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[41863,41948]},{"content":"figure 3","pos":[41956,41964]},{"content":"Figure 3.","pos":[42001,42010]},{"content":"Enable VBS","pos":[42011,42021]},{"pos":[42027,42158],"content":"Select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enabled<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> option, and then select <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Secure Boot and DMA Protection<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> from the <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Select Platform Security Level<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> list."},{"content":"figure 4","pos":[42166,42174]},{"content":"Figure 4.","pos":[42209,42218]},{"content":"Enable Secure Boot","pos":[42219,42237]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Device Guard Secure Boot is maximized when combined with DMA protection.","pos":[42244,42327]},{"content":"If your hardware contains the IOMMUs required for DMA protection, be sure to select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Secure Boot and DMA Protection<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> platform security level.","pos":[42328,42475]},{"content":"If your hardware does not contain IOMMU, there are several mitigations provided by leveraging Secure Boot without DMA Protection.","pos":[42476,42605]},{"content":"Close the Group Policy Management Editor, and then restart the Windows 10 test computer.","pos":[42616,42704]},{"content":"After you configure this setting, UEFI Secure Boot will be enabled upon restart.","pos":[42705,42785]},{"content":"Check the test computer’s event log for Device Guard GPOs.","pos":[42791,42849]},{"content":"Processed Device Guard policies are logged in event viewer at Application and Services Logs<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Microsoft<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>Windows<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>DeviceGuard-GPEXT<ph id=\"ph4\">\\\\</ph>Operational.","pos":[42859,43003]},{"content":"When the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Turn On Virtualization Based Security<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> policy is successfully processed, event ID 7000 is logged, which contains the selected settings within the policy.","pos":[43004,43169]},{"content":"Enable virtualization-based security of kernel-mode code integrity","pos":[43175,43241]},{"content":"Before you begin this process, verify that the desired computer meets the hardware requirements for VBS found in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Hardware considerations<ept id=\"p1\">](#hardware-considerations)</ept> section, and enable the Windows features discussed in the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Virtualization-based security Windows feature requirements<ept id=\"p2\">](#virtualization-based-security-windows-featurerrequirements)</ept> section.","pos":[43243,43600]},{"content":"When validated, you can enable virtualization-based protection of KMCI in one of two ways: manual configuration of the appropriate registry subkeys and Group Policy deployment.","pos":[43601,43777]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  All drivers on the system must be compatible with virtualization-based protection of code integrity; otherwise, your system may fail.","pos":[43780,43924]},{"content":"Microsoft recommends that you enable this feature on a group of test machines before you enable it on deployed machines.","pos":[43925,44045]},{"content":"To configure virtualization-based protection of KMCI manually:","pos":[44047,44109]},{"pos":[44115,44221],"content":"Navigate to the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>HKEY<ph id=\"ph1\">\\_</ph>LOCAL<ph id=\"ph2\">\\_</ph>MACHINE<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>SYSTEM<ph id=\"ph4\">\\\\</ph>CurrentControlSet<ph id=\"ph5\">\\\\</ph>Control<ph id=\"ph6\">\\\\</ph>DeviceGuard<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> registry subkey."},{"pos":[44226,44291],"content":"Set the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>HypervisorEnforcedCodeIntegrity DWORD<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> value to <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>1<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>."},{"content":"Restart the client computer.","pos":[44296,44324]},{"content":"It would be time consuming to perform these steps manually on every protected machine in your enterprise.","pos":[44326,44431]},{"content":"Instead, use Group Policy to deploy virtualization-based protection of KMCI.","pos":[44432,44508]},{"content":"This example creates a test OU called <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>DG Enabled PCs<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept>, which you will use to link the GPO.","pos":[44509,44600]},{"content":"If you prefer to link the policy to an existing OU rather than create a test OU and scope the policy by using appropriately named computer security groups, that is another option.","pos":[44601,44780]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Microsoft recommends that you test-enable this feature on a group of test computers before you deploy it to machines that are currently deployed to users.","pos":[44783,44948]},{"content":"If untested, there is a possibility that this feature can cause system instability and ultimately cause the client operating system to fail.","pos":[44949,45089]},{"content":"To use Group Policy to configure VBS of KMCI:","pos":[45091,45136]},{"pos":[45142,45279],"content":"Create a new GPO: Right-click the OU to which you want to link the GPO, and then click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Create a GPO in this domain, and Link it here<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"figure 5","pos":[45287,45295]},{"content":"Figure 5.","pos":[45334,45343]},{"content":"Create a new OU-linked GPO","pos":[45344,45370]},{"pos":[45376,45432],"content":"Name the new GPO <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Contoso VBS CI Protection GPO Test<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"This example uses <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>Contoso VBS CI Protection GPO Test<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> as the name of the GPO.","pos":[45438,45516]},{"content":"You can choose any name you prefer for this example.","pos":[45517,45569]},{"content":"Ideally, this name would align with your existing GPO naming convention.","pos":[45570,45642]},{"pos":[45648,45738],"content":"Open the Group Policy Management Editor: Right-click the new GPO, and then click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Edit<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"Within the selected GPO, navigate to Computer Configuration<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Administrative Templates<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>Device Guard.","pos":[45744,45852]},{"content":"Then, right-click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Turn On Virtualization Based Security<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and then click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Edit<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>.","pos":[45853,45938]},{"content":"figure 6","pos":[45946,45954]},{"content":"Figure 6.","pos":[45991,46000]},{"content":"Enable VBS","pos":[46001,46011]},{"pos":[46017,46139],"content":"Select the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Enabled<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> option, and then sele