rovides details of the available hardware-based security features as well as those features that are currently enabled.","pos":[51142,51289]},{"content":"For detailed information about what each property means, refer to Table 1.","pos":[51290,51364]},{"content":"Table 1.","pos":[51367,51375]},{"content":"Win32<ph id=\"ph1\">\\_</ph>DeviceGuard properties","pos":[51376,51405]},{"content":"Properties","pos":[51551,51561]},{"content":"Description","pos":[51601,51612]},{"content":"Valid values","pos":[51652,51664]},{"content":"AvailableSecurityProperties","pos":[51744,51771]},{"content":"This field helps to enumerate and report state on the relevant security properties for Device Guard.","pos":[51803,51903]},{"content":"If present, no relevant properties exist on the device.","pos":[51958,52013]},{"content":"If present, hypervisor support is available.","pos":[52050,52094]},{"content":"If present, Secure Boot is available.","pos":[52131,52168]},{"content":"If present, DMA protection is available.","pos":[52205,52245]},{"content":"InstanceIdentifier","pos":[52315,52333]},{"content":"A string that is unique to a particular device.","pos":[52365,52412]},{"content":"Determined by WMI.","pos":[52435,52453]},{"content":"RequiredSecurityProperties","pos":[52507,52533]},{"content":"This field describes the required security properties to enable virtualization-based security.","pos":[52565,52659]},{"content":"Nothing is required.","pos":[52714,52734]},{"content":"If present, Secure Boot is needed.","pos":[52771,52805]},{"content":"If present, DMA protection is needed.","pos":[52842,52879]},{"content":"If present, both Secure Boot and DMA protection are needed.","pos":[52916,52975]},{"content":"SecurityServicesConfigured","pos":[53045,53071]},{"content":"This field indicates whether the Credential Guard or HVCI service has been configured.","pos":[53103,53189]},{"content":"No services configured.","pos":[53244,53267]},{"content":"If present, Credential Guard is configured.","pos":[53304,53347]},{"content":"If present, HVCI is configured.","pos":[53384,53415]},{"content":"SecurityServicesRunning","pos":[53484,53507]},{"content":"This field indicates whether the Credential Guard or HVCI service is running.","pos":[53539,53616]},{"content":"No services running.","pos":[53671,53691]},{"content":"If present, Credential Guard is running.","pos":[53728,53768]},{"content":"If present, HVCI is running.","pos":[53805,53833]},{"content":"Version","pos":[53903,53910]},{"content":"This field lists the version of this WMI class.","pos":[53942,53989]},{"content":"The only valid value now is <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;strong&gt;</ph>1.0<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/strong&gt;</ph>.","pos":[54012,54061]},{"content":"VirtualizationBasedSecurityStatus","pos":[54115,54148]},{"content":"This field indicates whether VBS is enabled and running.","pos":[54180,54236]},{"content":"VBS is not enabled.","pos":[54291,54310]},{"content":"VBS is enabled but not running.","pos":[54347,54378]},{"content":"VBS is enabled and running.","pos":[54415,54442]},{"content":"PSComputerName","pos":[54512,54526]},{"content":"This field lists the computer name.","pos":[54558,54593]},{"content":"All valid values for computer name.","pos":[54616,54651]},{"content":"Another method to determine the available and enabled Device Guard features is to run msinfo32.exe from an elevated PowerShell session.","pos":[54682,54817]},{"content":"When you run this program, the Device Guard properties are displayed at the bottom of the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>System Summary<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> section, as shown in Figure 11.","pos":[54818,54959]},{"content":"figure 11","pos":[54963,54972]},{"content":"Figure 11.","pos":[55009,55019]},{"content":"Device Guard properties in the System Summary","pos":[55020,55065]},{"content":"Catalog files","pos":[55070,55083]},{"content":"Enforcement of Device Guard on a system requires that every trusted application have a signature or its binary hashes added to the code integrity policy.","pos":[55085,55238]},{"content":"For many organizations, this can be an issue when considering unsigned LOB applications.","pos":[55239,55327]},{"content":"To avoid the requirement that organizations repackage and sign these applications, Windows 10 includes a tool called Package Inspector that monitors an installation process for any deployed and executed binary files.","pos":[55328,55544]},{"content":"If the tool discovers such files, it itemizes them in a catalog file.","pos":[55545,55614]},{"content":"These catalog files offer you a way to trust your existing unsigned applications, whether developed in house or by a third party, as well as trust signed applications for which you do not want to trust the signer but rather the specific application.","pos":[55615,55864]},{"content":"When created, these files can be signed, the signing certificates added to your existing code integrity policies, and the catalog files themselves distributed to the clients.","pos":[55865,56039]},{"pos":[56042,56157],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  The Enterprise edition of Windows 10 or Windows Server 2016 is required to create and use catalog files."},{"content":"Create catalog files","pos":[56163,56183]},{"content":"The creation of catalog files is the first step to add an unsigned application to a code integrity policy.","pos":[56185,56291]},{"content":"To create a catalog file, copy each of the following commands into an elevated Windows PowerShell session, and then complete the steps:","pos":[56292,56427]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  When you establish a naming convention it makes it easier to detect deployed catalog files in the future.","pos":[56430,56546]},{"content":"In this guide, you will use <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt><ph id=\"ph1\">\\*</ph>-Contoso.cat<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> as the naming convention.","pos":[56547,56617]},{"content":"For more information about why this practice is helpful to inventory or detect catalog files, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Inventory catalog files with System Center Configuration Manager<ept id=\"p1\">](#inventory-catalog-files-with-system-center-configuration-manager)</ept> section.","pos":[56618,56862]},{"content":"Be sure that a code integrity policy is currently running in audit mode.","pos":[56869,56941]},{"content":"Package Inspector does not always detect installation files that have been removed from the machine during the installation process.","pos":[56947,57079]},{"content":"To ensure that these binaries are also trusted, the code integrity policy that you created and audited in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Create code integrity policies from golden PCs<ept id=\"p1\">](#create-code-integrity-policies-from-golden-pcs)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Audit code integrity policies<ept id=\"p2\">](#audit-code-integrity-policies)</ept> sections should be deployed, in audit mode, to the system on which you are running Package Inspector.","pos":[57080,57457]},{"pos":[57463,57711],"content":"**Note**  \nThis process should **not** be performed on a system running an enforced Device Guard policy, only with a policy running in audit mode. If a policy is currently being enforced, you will not be able to install and run the application.","leadings":["","    "],"nodes":[{"content":"Note","pos":[2,6]},{"content":"This process should **not** be performed on a system running an enforced Device Guard policy, only with a policy running in audit mode. If a policy is currently being enforced, you will not be able to install and run the application.","pos":[11,244],"nodes":[{"content":"This process should <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>not<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> be performed on a system running an enforced Device Guard policy, only with a policy running in audit mode.","pos":[0,135]},{"content":"If a policy is currently being enforced, you will not be able to install and run the application.","pos":[136,233]}]}]},{"content":"Start Package Inspector, and then scan drive C:","pos":[57717,57764]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Package inspector can monitor installations on any local drive.","pos":[57808,57882]},{"content":"In this example, we install the application on drive C, but any other drive can be used.","pos":[57883,57971]},{"content":"Copy the installation media to drive C.","pos":[57981,58020]},{"content":"By copying the installation media to drive C, you ensure that Package Inspector detects and catalogs the actual installer.","pos":[58026,58148]},{"content":"If you skip this step, the future code integrity policy may trust the application to run but not be installed.","pos":[58149,58259]},{"content":"Install and launch the application.","pos":[58265,58300]},{"pos":[58306,58617],"content":"Install the application to drive C. When the installation is finished, launch the application and ensure that any product updates are installed and any downloadable content caught during the scan. When finished, close and \nreopen the application once again to ensure that the scan has captured all binaries.","leadings":["","    "],"nodes":[{"content":"Install the application to drive C. When the installation is finished, launch the application and ensure that any product updates are installed and any downloadable content caught during the scan.","pos":[0,196]},{"content":"When finished, close and reopen the application once again to ensure that the scan has captured all binaries.","pos":[197,307]}]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>      Every binary that is run while Package Inspector is running will be captured in the catalog.","pos":[58628,58735]},{"content":"Therefore, be sure not to run additional installations or updates during the scan to minimize the risk of trusting the incorrect binaries.","pos":[58736,58874]},{"content":"Alternatively, if you want to add multiple applications to a single catalog file, simply repeat the installation and run process 