ialog box, select <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Variable or path name<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, and then type <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>C:<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Windows<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System32<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>catroot<ph id=\"ph4\">\\\\</ph>{F750E6C3-38EE-11D1-85E5-00C04FC295EE}<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> in the box, as shown in Figure 21."},{"content":"figure 21","pos":[73848,73857]},{"content":"Figure 21.","pos":[73904,73914]},{"content":"Set the path properties","pos":[73915,73938]},{"pos":[73944,73957],"content":"Click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>OK<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"Now that you have created the client settings policy, right-click the new policy, click <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Deploy<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and then choose the collection on which you would like to inventory the catalog files.","pos":[73963,74149]},{"content":"At the time of the next software inventory cycle, when the targeted clients receive the new client settings policy, you will be able to view the inventoried files in the built-in System Center Configuration Manager reports or Resource Explorer.","pos":[74150,74394]},{"content":"To view the inventoried files on a client within Resource Explorer, complete the following steps:","pos":[74395,74492]},{"content":"Open the Configuration Manager console, and select the Assets and Compliance workspace.","pos":[74498,74585]},{"content":"Navigate to Overview<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Devices, and search for the device on which you want to view the inventoried files.","pos":[74590,74695]},{"pos":[74700,74783],"content":"Right-click the computer, point to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Start<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, and then click <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Resource Explorer<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>."},{"content":"In Resource Explorer, navigate to Software<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>File Details to view the inventoried catalog files.","pos":[74788,74883]},{"pos":[74886,75072],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  If nothing is displayed in this view, navigate to Software<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Last Software Scan in Resource Explorer to verify that the client has recently completed a software inventory scan."},{"content":"Code integrity policies","pos":[75078,75101]},{"content":"Code integrity policies maintain the standards by which a computer running Windows 10 determines whether an application is trustworthy and can be run.","pos":[75103,75253]},{"content":"For an overview of code integrity, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configurable code integrity<ept id=\"p1\">](#configurable-code-integrity)</ept> section.","pos":[75254,75365]},{"content":"A common system imaging practice in today’s IT organization is to establish a “golden” image as a reference for what an ideal system should look like, and then use that image to clone additional company assets.","pos":[75367,75577]},{"content":"Code integrity policies follow a similar methodology, that begins with the establishment of a golden PC.","pos":[75578,75682]},{"content":"Like when imaging, you can have multiple golden PCs based on model, department, application set, and so on.","pos":[75683,75790]},{"content":"Although the thought process around the creation of code integrity policies is similar to imaging, these policies should be maintained independently.","pos":[75791,75940]},{"content":"Assess the necessity of additional code integrity policies based on what should be allowed to be installed and run and for whom.","pos":[75941,76069]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Each machine can have only <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>one<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> code integrity policy at a time.","pos":[76072,76150]},{"content":"Whichever way you deploy this policy, it is renamed to SIPolicy.p7b and copied to C:<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Windows<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System32<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>CodeIntegrity.","pos":[76151,76270]},{"content":"Keep this in mind when you create your code integrity policies.","pos":[76271,76334]},{"content":"Optionally, code integrity policies can align with your software catalog as well as any IT department–approved applications.","pos":[76336,76460]},{"content":"One simple method to implement code integrity policies is to use existing images to create one master code integrity policy.","pos":[76461,76585]},{"content":"You do so by creating a code integrity policy from each image, and then by merging the policies.","pos":[76586,76682]},{"content":"This way, what is installed on all of those images will be allowed to run, should the applications be installed on a computer based on a different image.","pos":[76683,76836]},{"content":"Alternatively, you may choose to create a base applications policy and add policies based on the computer’s role or department.","pos":[76837,76964]},{"content":"Organizations have a choice of how their policies are created, merged or serviced, and managed.","pos":[76965,77060]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  The following section assumes that you will deploy code integrity policies as part of your Device Guard deployment.","pos":[77063,77189]},{"content":"Alternatively, configurable code integrity is available without the enablement of Device Guard.","pos":[77190,77285]},{"content":"Code integrity policy rules","pos":[77291,77318]},{"content":"Code integrity policies consist of several components.","pos":[77320,77374]},{"content":"The two major components, which are configurable, are called <bpt id=\"p1\">*</bpt>policy rules<ept id=\"p1\">*</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>file rules<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept>, respectively.","pos":[77375,77482]},{"content":"Code integrity policy rules are options that the code integrity policy creator can specify on the policy.","pos":[77483,77588]},{"content":"These options include the enablement of audit mode, UMCI, and so on.","pos":[77589,77657]},{"content":"You can modify these options in a new or existing code integrity policy.","pos":[77658,77730]},{"content":"File rules are the level to which the code integrity policy scan ties each binary trust.","pos":[77731,77819]},{"content":"For example, the hash level is going to itemize each discovered hash on the system within the generated code integrity policy.","pos":[77820,77946]},{"content":"This way, when a binary prepares to run, the code integrity service will validate its hash value against the trusted hashes found in the code integrity policy.","pos":[77947,78106]},{"content":"Based on that result, the binary will or will not be allowed to run.","pos":[78107,78175]},{"content":"To modify the policy rule options of an existing code integrity policy, use the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Set-RuleOption<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> Windows PowerShell cmdlet.","pos":[78177,78302]},{"content":"Note the following examples of how to use this cmdlet to add and remove a rule option on an existing code integrity policy:","pos":[78303,78426]},{"content":"To enable UMCI, add rule option 0 to an existing policy by running the following command:","pos":[78432,78521]},{"content":"To disable UMCI on an existing code integrity policy, remove rule option 0 by running the following command:","pos":[78586,78694]},{"content":"You can set several rule options within a code integrity policy.","pos":[78764,78828]},{"content":"Table 2 lists each rule and its high-level meaning.","pos":[78829,78880]},{"content":"Table 2.","pos":[78887,78895]},{"content":"Code integrity policy - policy rule options","pos":[78896,78939]},{"content":"Rule option","pos":[78943,78954]},{"content":"Description","pos":[78957,78968]},{"content":"0 Enabled:UMCI","pos":[79005,79019]},{"content":"Code integrity policies restrict both kernel-mode and user-mode binaries.","pos":[79024,79097]},{"content":"By default, only kernel-mode binaries are restricted.","pos":[79098,79151]},{"content":"Enabling this rule option validates user mode executables and scripts.","pos":[79152,79222]},{"content":"1 Enabled:Boot Menu Protection","pos":[79229,79259]},{"content":"This option is not currently supported.","pos":[79264,79303]},{"content":"2 Required:WHQL","pos":[79310,79325]},{"content":"By default, legacy drivers that are not Windows Hardware Quality Labs (WHQL) signed are allowed to execute.","pos":[79330,79437]},{"content":"Enabling this rule requires that every executed driver is WHQL signed and removes legacy driver support.","pos":[79438,79542]},{"content":"Going forward, every new Windows 10–compatible driver must be WHQL certified.","pos":[79543,79620]},{"content":"3 Enabled:Audit Mode (Default)","pos":[79627,79657]},{"content":"Enables the execution of binaries outside of the code integrity policy but logs each occurrence in the CodeIntegrity event log, which can be used to update the existing policy before enforcement.","pos":[79662,79857]},{"content":"To enforce a code integrity policy, remove this option.","pos":[79858,79913]},{"content":"4 Disabled:Flight Signing","pos":[79920,79945]},{"content":"If enabled, code integrity policies will not trust flightroot-signed binaries.","pos":[79950,80028]},{"content":"This would be used in the scenario in which organizations only want to run released binaries, not flighted builds.","pos":[80029,80143]},{"content":"5 Enabled:Inherent Default Policy","pos":[80150,80183]},{"content":"This option is not currently supported.","pos":[80188,80227]},{"content":"6 Enabled:Unsigned System Integrity Policy (Default)","pos":[80234,80286]},{"content":"Allows the policy to remain unsigned.","pos":[80291,80328]},{"content":"When this option is removed, the policy must be signed and have UpdatePolicySigners added to the policy to enable future policy modifications.","pos":[80329,80471]},{"content":"7 Allowed:Debug Policy Augmented","pos":[80478,80510]},{"content":"This option is not currently supported.","pos":[80515,80554]},{"content":"8 Required:EV Signers","pos":[80561,80582]},{"content":"In addition to being WHQL signed, this rule requires that drivers must have been submitted by a partner that has an Extended Verification (EV) certificate.","pos":[80587,80742]},{"content":"All future Windows 10 and later drivers will meet this requirement.","pos":[80743,80810]},{"content":"9 Enabled:Advanced Boot Options Menu","pos":[80817,80853]},{"content":"The F8 preboot menu is disabled by default for all code integrity policies.","pos":[80858,80933]},{"content":"Setting this rule option allows the F8 menu to appear to physically present users.","pos":[80934,81016]},{"content":"10 Enabled:Boot Audit on Failure","pos":[81023,81055]},{"content":"Used when the code integrity policy is in enforcement mode.","pos":[81060,81119]},{"content":"When a driver fails during startup, the code integrity policy will be placed in audit mode so that Windows will load.","pos":[81120,81237]},{"content":"Administrators can validate the reason for the failure in the CodeIntegrity event log.","pos":[81238,81324]},{"content":"File rule levels allow administrators to specify the level at which they want to trust their applications.","pos":[81327,81433]},{"content":"This level of trust could be as low as the hash of each binary and as high as a PCA certificate.","pos":[81434,81530]},{"content":"File rule levels are specified both when you create a new code integrity policy from a scan and when you create a policy from audit events.","pos":[81531,81670]},{"content":"In addition, to combine rule levels found in multiple policies, you can merge the policies.","pos":[81671,81762]},{"content":"When merged, code integrity policies combine their file rules.","pos":[81763,81825]},{"content":"Each file rule level has its benefit and disadvantage.","pos":[81826,81880]},{"content":"Use Table 3 to select the appropriate protection level for your available administrative resources and Device Guard deployment scenario.","pos":[81881,82017]},{"content":"Table 3.","pos":[82024,82032]},{"content":"Code integrity policy - file rule levels","pos":[82033,82073]},{"content":"Rule level","pos":[82077,82087]},{"content":"Description","pos":[82090,82101]},{"content":"Hash","pos":[82137,82141]},{"content":"Specifies individual hash values for each discovered binary.","pos":[82146,82206]},{"content":"Although this level is specific, it can cause additional administrative overhead to maintain the current product versions’ hash values.","pos":[82207,82342]},{"content":"Each time a binary is updated, the hash value changes, therefore requiring a policy update.","pos":[82343,82434]},{"content":"FileName","pos":[82441,82449]},{"content":"Specifies individual binary file names.","pos":[82454,82493]},{"content":"Although the hash values for an application are modified when updated, the file names are typically not.","pos":[82494,82598]},{"content":"This offers less specific security than the hash level but does not typically require a policy update when any binary is modified.","pos":[82599,82729]},{"content":"SignedVersion","pos":[82736,82749]},{"content":"This combines the publisher rule with a version number.","pos":[82754,82809]},{"content":"This option allows anything from the specified publisher, with a version at or above the specified version number, to run.","pos":[82810,82932]},{"content":"Publisher","pos":[82939,82948]},{"content":"This is a combination of the PCA certificate and the common name (CN) on the leaf certificate.","pos":[82953,83047]},{"content":"In the scenario that a PCA certificate is used to sign multiple companies’ applications (such as VeriSign), this rule level allows organizations to trust the PCA certificate but only for the company whose name is on the leaf certificate (for example, Intel for device drivers).","pos":[83048,83325]},{"content":"This level trusts a certificate with a long validity period but only when combined with a trusted leaf certificate.","pos":[83326,83441]},{"content":"FilePublisher","pos":[83448,83461]},{"content":"This is a combination of “FileName” plus “Publisher” (PCA certificate with CN of leaf) plus a minimum version number.","pos":[83466,83583]},{"content":"This option trusts specific files from the specified publisher, with a version at or above the specified version number.","pos":[83584,83704]},{"content":"LeafCertificate","pos":[83711,83726]},{"content":"Adds trusted signers at the individual signing certificate level.","pos":[83731,83796]},{"content":"The benefit of using this level versus the individual hash level is that new versions of the product will have different hash values but typically the same signing certificate.","pos":[83797,83973]},{"content":"Using this level, no policy update would be needed to run the new version of the application.","pos":[83974,84067]},{"content":"However, leaf certificates have much shorter validity periods than PCA certificates, so additional administrative overhead is associated with updating the code integrity policy when these certificates expire.","pos":[84068,84276]},{"content":"PcaCertificate","pos":[84283,84297]},{"content":"Adds the highest certificate in the provided certificate chain to signers.","pos":[84302,84376]},{"content":"This is typically one certificate below the root certificate, because the scan does not validate anything above the presented signature by going online or checking local root stores.","pos":[84377,84559]},{"content":"RootCertificate","pos":[84566,84581]},{"content":"Currently unsupported.","pos":[84586,84608]},{"content":"WHQL","pos":[84615,84619]},{"content":"Trusts binaries if they have been validated and signed by WHQL.","pos":[84624,84687]},{"content":"This is primarily for kernel binaries.","pos":[84688,84726]},{"content":"WHQLPublisher","pos":[84733,84746]},{"content":"This is a combination of the WHQL and the CN on the leaf certificate and is primarily for kernel binaries.","pos":[84751,84857]},{"content":"WHQLFilePublisher","pos":[84864,84881]},{"content":"Specifies that the binaries are validated and signed by WHQL, with a specific publisher (WHQLPublisher), and that the binary is the specified version or newer.","pos":[84886,85045]},{"content":"This is primarily for kernel binaries.","pos":[85046,85084]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  When you create code integrity policies with the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>New-CIPolicy<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> cmdlet, you can specify a primary file rule level by including the <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>–Level<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> parameter.","pos":[85089,85254]},{"content":"For discovered binaries that cannot be trusted based on the primary file rule criteria, use the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>–Fallback<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> parameter.","pos":[85255,85375]},{"content":"For example, if the primary file rule level is PCACertificate but you would like to trust the unsigned applications as well, using the Hash rule level as a fallback adds the hash values of binaries that did not have a signing certificate.","pos":[85376,85614]},{"content":"Create code integrity policies from golden PCs","pos":[85620,85666]},{"content":"The process to create a golden code integrity policy from a reference system is straightforward.","pos":[85668,85764]},{"content":"This section outlines the process that is required to successfully create a code integrity policy with Windows PowerShell.","pos":[85765,85887]},{"content":"First, for this example, you must initiate variables to be used during the creation process.","pos":[85888,85980]},{"content":"Rather than using variables, you can simply use the full file paths in the command.","pos":[85981,86064]},{"content":"Next, you create the code integrity policy by scanning the system for installed applications.","pos":[86065,86158]},{"content":"When created, the policy file is converted to binary format so that Windows can consume its contents.","pos":[86159,86260]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Before you begin this procedure, ensure that the reference PC is clean of viruses or malware.","pos":[86263,86367]},{"content":"Each piece of installed software should be validated as trustworthy before you create this policy.","pos":[86368,86466]},{"content":"Also, be sure that any software that you would like to be scanned is installed on the system before you create the code integrity policy.","pos":[86467,86604]},{"content":"To create a code integrity policy, copy each of the following commands into an elevated Windows PowerShell session, in order:","pos":[86606,86731]},{"content":"Initialize variables that you will use:","pos":[86737,86776]},{"content":"Create a new code integrity policy by scanning the system for installed applications:","pos":[86944,87029]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  By specifying the <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>–UserPEs<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> parameter, rule option <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>0 Enabled:UMCI<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> is automatically added to the code integrity policy.","pos":[87133,87267]},{"content":"If you do not specify this parameter, use the following command to enable UMCI:","pos":[87268,87347]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  You can add the <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>–Fallback<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> parameter to catch any applications not discovered using the primary file rule level specified by the <bpt id=\"p3\">*</bpt>–Level<ept id=\"p3\">*</ept> parameter.","pos":[87418,87578]},{"content":"For more information about file rule level options, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Code integrity policy rules<ept id=\"p1\">](#code-integrity-policy-rules)</ept> section.","pos":[87579,87707]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  If you would like to specify the code integrity policy scan to look only at a specific drive, you can do so by using the <bpt id=\"p2\">*</bpt>–ScanPath<ept id=\"p2\">*</ept> parameter.","pos":[87716,87870]},{"content":"Without this parameter, as shown in the example, the entire system is scanned.","pos":[87871,87949]},{"content":"Convert the code integrity policy to a binary format:","pos":[87955,88008]},{"content":"After you complete these steps, the Device Guard binary file (DeviceGuardPolicy.bin) and original .xml file (IntialScan.xml) will be available on your desktop.","pos":[88068,88227]},{"content":"You can use the binary version as a code integrity policy or sign it for additional security.","pos":[88228,88321]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Microsoft recommends that you keep the original .xml file of the policy for use when you need to merge the code integrity policy with another policy or update its rule options.","pos":[88324,88511]},{"content":"Alternatively, you would have to create a new policy from a new scan for servicing.","pos":[88512,88595]},{"content":"For more information about how to merge code integrity policies, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Merge code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">](#merge-code-integrity-policies)</ept> section.","pos":[88596,88741]},{"content":"Microsoft recommends that every code integrity policy be run in audit mode before being enforced.","pos":[88743,88840]},{"content":"Doing so allows administrators to discover any issues with the policy without receiving error message dialog boxes.","pos":[88841,88956]},{"content":"For information about how to audit a code integrity policy, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Audit code integrity policies<ept id=\"p1\">](#audit-code-integrity-policies)</ept> section.","pos":[88957,89097]},{"content":"Audit code integrity policies","pos":[89103,89132]},{"content":"When code integrity policies are run in audit mode, it allows administrators to discover any applications that were missed during an initial policy scan and to identify any new applications that have been installed and run since the original policy was created.","pos":[89134,89395]},{"content":"While a code integrity policy is running in audit mode, any binary that runs and would have been denied had the policy been enforced is logged in the Applications and Services Logs<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Microsoft<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>CodeIntegrity<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>Operational event log.","pos":[89396,89626]},{"content":"When these logged binaries have been validated, they can easily be added to a new code integrity policy.","pos":[89627,89731]},{"content":"When the new exception policy is created, you can merge it with your existing code integrity policies.","pos":[89732,89834]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note:<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  Before you begin this process, you need to create a code integrity policy binary file.","pos":[89837,89934]},{"content":"If you have not already done so, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Create an audit code integrity policy<ept id=\"p1\">](#create-an-audit-code-integrity-policy)</ept> section for a step-by-step walkthrough of the process to create a code integrity policy and convert it to binary format.","pos":[89935,90176]},{"content":"To audit a code integrity policy with local policy:","pos":[90178,90229]},{"pos":[90235,90441],"content":"Copy the DeviceGuardPolicy.bin file that you created in the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Create code integrity policies from golden PCs<ept id=\"p1\">](#create-code-integrity-policies-from-golden-pcs)</ept> section to C:<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Windows<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System32<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>CodeIntegrity."},{"pos":[90446,90552],"content":"On the system you want to run in audit mode, open the Local Group Policy Editor by running <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GPEdit.msc<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>."},{"content":"Navigate to Computer Configuration<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Administrative Templates<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>Device Guard, and then select <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Deploy Code Integrity Policy<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[90557,90690]},{"content":"Enable this setting by using the file path C:<ph id=\"ph1\">\\\\</ph>Windows<ph id=\"ph2\">\\\\</ph>System32<ph id=\"ph3\">\\\\</ph>CodeIntegrity<ph id=